item.title: In the World's Coronavirus Blind Spot, Fears of a Silent Epidemic
item.description: Limited testing capacity and spikes in undiagnosed respiratory illnesses have raised concerns across sub-Saharan Africa that the virus could be spreading unnoticed, deepening the continent’s economic crisis.

item.title: Fearing Hong Kong's Fate, Taiwan Moves to Bolster Its Military Against China
item.description: Beijing’s crushing of pro-democracy forces in Hong Kong has deepened Taiwanese fear and resentment of China’s Communist Party, injecting new energy into the island democracy’s efforts to build up its military defenses.

item.title: Shinzo Abe's Lesson for U.S.: Leaning on a Central Bank Has Its Limits
item.description: Japan’s next leader will face a question many other countries are now grappling with because of the coronavirus pandemic: How much can central banks do to pull economies out of a deep malaise?

item.title: Covid-19 Forces 100,000 Venezuelan Migrants Back to Broken Country
item.description: Among the millions of Venezuelans who have fled their homeland for other Latin American countries in recent years, more than 100,000 have returned after coronavirus lockdowns shattered their lives anew.

item.title: Iran Scales Back Religious Festival, but Some Rush to Holiday Destinations
item.description: Iran allowed thousands of its Shia faithful to gather for one of the Islamic sect’s most important religious holidays, the latest attempt on the part of leaders to preserve a sense of normalcy even as the country grapples with high infection rates from coronavirus.

item.title: Belarus's Struggle to Escape Its Soviet Past Pushes It Into Russia's Embrace
item.description: The long rule of Alexander Lukashenko has left his country economically depleted and reliant on Russia, largely trapped in its Soviet-era past and likely bound to Moscow for many years to come.
